[[File:Macrobius, universe with the earth in the centre.jpg|thumb|300x300px|The Universe with the earth in the centre according to Macrobius (''Diagram in folio 25 recto'').]]
'''Commentary on Cicero's Dream of Scipio''' (in [[Latin]] ''Commentarii in Somnium Scipionis'') is a philosophical treatise of [[Macrobius]] based on the [[Somnium Scipionis|famous dream]] narrated in ''[[De re publica|On the republic]]'' of [[Cicero]] (Chapter VI, 9-29), in which [[Scipio Africanus|Scipion the African]] the Old appears  to his adoptive grandson, [[Scipio Aemilianus|Scipion Emiliano]], and reveals him his future destination and the one of his country, explains the rewards that await to the [[Virtue|virtuous]] man in another life, describes the universe and the place of the Earth and the man inside the universe. Macrobius, his author, does not offer an exhaustive comment of the text ''ciceroniano'', but it exposes a series of ''theories on the dreams'' from [[Neoplatonism|neoplatónic]] background, on ''the mystic properties of the numbers'', on ''the nature of the'' ''[[soul]]'', on [[astronomy]] and on [[Music]]. Macrobius quotes a lot of authorities, but is little likely that have read them all or at least the majority. [[Plotinus|Plotino]] and [[Porphyry (philosopher)|Porfirio]] are his main sources and quotes frequently to [[Virgil]] with ornamental purpose. Nevertheless, the work incorporates ideas of the [[neoplatonism]], that are not conserved  in a direct form in any another place. The style is quite uneven, since Macrobius copies or translates his sources without unifying the style.

